A large number of companies have put their databases and product catalogues on the Web , search engines allow electronic market participants around the globe to locate poten- tial trading partners , and a set of different protocols are established to exchange goods and services by using different business models and following different strategies . The purpose of this workshop is to discuss the technical and the business issues of electronic commerce as well as the problems that emerge at the intersection of business and technology . In particular , we are interested in papers that deal with the security , the integrity , the trust , the availability , the privacy , the fairness , the legal aspects and other issues critical for the success of future electronic commerce . Papers on industrial experience in this area are also welcome . The main objective of the workshop is to bring together researchers from different disciplines , developers , and users all interested in the critical success factors of electronic commerce systems . We invite papers , short papers , work-in-progress reports , industrial experiences describing advances in all areas of security and electronic commerce applications , including , but not limited to the areas of : - authentication , authorisation and access control , - heterogeneous information , multi-database systems , - intellectual property , watermarking , notarisation services , - multimedia databases , virtual malls , and kiosk systems , - agent technology , locating services , - web documents , digital libraries and publishing environments , - applied cryptography , key management , certification - requirements for specific market structures , - attack analysis , information filtering , practical experiences , - information warfare , public and govermental policies , - trading digital goods , electronic negotiation , - new forms of auctions , brokerages , and marketplaces - application fields , like virtual banking , elect . intermediaries - architectures for secure and fair electronic commerce , - business processes , transactions , and workflow management , - users , organisational requirements and settings , - data mining , data warehousing and legacy systems , - risk , economic security cost and benefit models , - auditing , intrusion detection , administration tools , - common practice , legal and regulatory issues , - electronic cash , wallets , pay-per-view systems , - security paradigm shifts , new definitions of security , - privacy , anonymity , pseudo anonymity , and trust , - . . . SUBMISSION DETAILS - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - Authors are invited to submit papers describing both theoretical and practical work dealing with the above or related issues . Papers which describe ongoing research or provide an excellent surveying work are welcome too . Papers should be in English and may be submitted as regular papers ( up to 5000 words ) or short papers ( up to 2500 words ) . The cover page should include the name and affiliation of the author ( s ) , contact address , e-mail , fax and telephone . Electronic submission is preferred .
